% ==================== ABSTRACT ====================
\begin{abstract}
Digital images can be manipulated in ways that are invisible to the human eye. Detecting such tampering and pinpointing exactly which pixels were altered is a challenging problem in image forensics. This report presents a systematic ablation study for pixel-level image tamper detection and localization on the CASIA~v2.0 benchmark dataset (12,614 images). The final system uses a UNet segmentation model with a pretrained ResNet-34 encoder, Error Level Analysis (ELA) preprocessing, and CBAM attention modules. Through 60+ controlled experiments across four research tracks, we established a clear finding: \textbf{input representation matters most}. Switching from raw RGB images to Multi-Quality RGB ELA (9-channel) input produced a +34.19 percentage point improvement in Pixel~F1 --- more than all other improvements combined. The best model (vR.P.19) achieves a \textbf{Pixel~F1 of 0.7965}, \textbf{IoU of 0.6615}, and \textbf{Pixel~AUC of 0.9665}. Every experiment followed a strict single-variable ablation discipline (one change per experiment), enabling clear cause-and-effect analysis.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Image tampering detection, image forgery localization, error level analysis, UNet segmentation, ablation study, CASIA dataset.
\end{IEEEkeywords}


% ==================== INTRODUCTION ====================
\section{Introduction}

Digital images are ubiquitous in journalism, law enforcement, scientific research, and social media. However, modern image editing tools make it easy to manipulate photographs in ways that are nearly undetectable by the human eye. Common types of tampering include:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Splicing:} Copying a region from one image and pasting it into another.
    \item \textbf{Copy-move:} Duplicating a part of an image within the same image, often to hide or fabricate content.
\end{itemize}

Detecting whether an image has been tampered with (\textit{detection}) is useful, but knowing \textit{where} the tampering occurred (\textit{localization}) is far more valuable. This project tackles both tasks: given an input image, the system produces a binary mask highlighting the tampered pixels.

Building such a system is difficult for several reasons. First, tampered regions often occupy a very small fraction of the image (sometimes less than 2\% of all pixels), creating a severe class imbalance at the pixel level. Second, skilled forgers adjust lighting, color, and compression to make edits blend seamlessly with the surrounding content. Third, JPEG compression artifacts can either mask or mimic tampering traces, complicating forensic analysis.

This report describes a systematic approach to solving this problem. Rather than building a single model and reporting its results, we conducted \textbf{60+ controlled experiments} across four research tracks, changing exactly one variable at a time. This ablation methodology allows us to determine \textit{what actually works and why}, rather than relying on guesswork or combining multiple changes simultaneously.

The key contributions of this work are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item A complete pipeline from raw images to pixel-level tamper localization using ELA preprocessing and pretrained UNet segmentation.
    \item A rigorous ablation study establishing that \textbf{input representation dominates all other factors} --- the single biggest improvement came from how we preprocess the image, not from architecture or training tricks.
    \item Transparent documentation of both successes and failures, including three failed research tracks that provided lessons directly shaping the final approach.
    \item Full reproducibility via Weights~\&~Biases experiment tracking and fixed random seeds.
    \item Open-source code and experiment logs available publicly.\footnote{GitHub: \url{https://github.com/The-Harsh-Vardhan/TIDAL-Tampered_Image_Detection_And_Localization}}\textsuperscript{,}\footnote{W\&B Report: \url{https://api.wandb.ai/links/tampered-image-detection-and-localization/w5fy6lb0}}
\end{itemize}


% ==================== RELATED WORK ====================
\section{Related Work}

Image forgery detection has been studied extensively over the past decade. This section reviews the main approaches that influenced our work.

\subsection{Traditional Forensic Methods}

Early forgery detection relied on hand-crafted features such as JPEG compression artifacts~\cite{bianchi2012jpeg}, noise inconsistencies, and Color Filter Array (CFA) patterns. Error Level Analysis (ELA)~\cite{krawetz2007picture} is one such technique: it re-saves an image at a given JPEG quality and measures the difference from the original. Tampered regions that were compressed at different quality levels show inconsistent residuals. While these methods are interpretable, they struggle with sophisticated forgeries and produce high false-positive rates when used alone.

\subsection{CNN-Based Approaches}

Deep learning transformed forgery detection by learning features directly from data. Nagm~et~al.~\cite{nagm2024etasr} combined ELA preprocessing with a custom CNN for binary classification (tampered vs.\ authentic), achieving 96.21\% accuracy on CASIA~v2.0 (JPEG-only subset). However, classification-only models cannot localize the tampered region --- they answer ``is it tampered?'' but not ``where?''

\subsection{Segmentation-Based Localization}

To achieve pixel-level localization, researchers adopted encoder-decoder architectures. The UNet~\cite{ronneberger2015unet}, originally designed for biomedical image segmentation, proved effective for tamper localization. Using pretrained encoders (e.g., ResNet~\cite{he2016resnet} trained on ImageNet~\cite{deng2009imagenet}) significantly improves performance on small forensic datasets by providing rich, generalizable feature representations. Nested variants like UNet++~\cite{zhou2018unetplusplus} further improve boundary delineation through dense skip connections.

\subsection{Attention Mechanisms}

Attention modules help the model focus on the most relevant features. CBAM (Convolutional Block Attention Module)~\cite{woo2018cbam} applies both channel-wise and spatial attention, teaching the model which feature maps and which spatial locations are most important. In our experiments, CBAM provided one of the most parameter-efficient improvements.

\subsection{Multi-Stream and Frequency-Domain Methods}

Recent state-of-the-art systems such as EMT-Net~\cite{emtnet2023} combine multiple input streams (RGB, noise maps, frequency features) using Swin Transformers, achieving AUC of 0.987 on the NIST dataset. SRM (Spatial Rich Model) noise filters~\cite{fridrich2012srm} extract high-pass noise residuals that reveal manipulation traces invisible in normal images. Bayar and Stamm~\cite{bayar2018constrained} proposed constrained convolutional layers that learn manipulation-specific features, while ManTra-Net~\cite{wu2019mantranet} introduced anomaly detection for forgery localization without requiring per-dataset fine-tuning. These techniques represent the current frontier, but require significantly more computational resources.


% ==================== DATASET ====================
\section{Dataset}

\subsection{CASIA v2.0}

All experiments use the \textbf{CASIA v2.0} dataset~\cite{dong2013casia}, a widely-used benchmark for image forgery detection and localization. Table~\ref{tab:dataset} summarizes its key properties.

