\subsection{Error Level Analysis (ELA) Preprocessing}

ELA is a forensic preprocessing technique that reveals compression inconsistencies in images. It works as follows:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Load the original image as RGB.
    \item Re-save it as a JPEG at a specific quality level~$Q$.
    \item Reload the recompressed image.
    \item Compute the pixel-wise absolute difference between the original and the recompressed version.
    \item Scale the brightness so the maximum difference maps to 255.
\end{enumerate}

Authentic regions compress uniformly and show low ELA residuals. Tampered regions, which were saved at different compression levels or composited from different sources, show inconsistencies that appear as bright artifacts in the ELA map.

\textbf{Multi-Quality RGB ELA (Best Variant):} Instead of using a single quality level, the best configuration uses three quality levels --- $Q=75$, $Q=85$, and $Q=95$ --- each producing an RGB ELA map. These three maps are stacked to form a 9-channel input tensor ($3~\text{qualities} \times 3~\text{RGB channels} = 9~\text{channels}$). Each quality level captures different types and strengths of compression artifacts:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Q=75 (aggressive)}: Produces large residuals; good at catching strong manipulations.
    \item \textbf{Q=85 (balanced)}: Medium residuals; a general-purpose level.
    \item \textbf{Q=95 (gentle)}: Small residuals; sensitive to subtle edits.
\end{itemize}


