Random seed & 42 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}


\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}

We use the following metrics to evaluate model performance, computed on \textbf{tampered images only} (since authentic images trivially score perfect masks):

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Pixel F1:} The primary metric. Harmonic mean of pixel-level precision and recall. Measures how well the predicted mask overlaps with the ground truth mask.
    \item \textbf{IoU (Jaccard):} Intersection over Union between predicted and ground truth masks. A stricter metric than F1.
    \item \textbf{Pixel AUC:} Area under the ROC curve at the pixel level. Threshold-independent measure of discrimination quality.
    \item \textbf{Image Accuracy:} Binary classification accuracy --- what fraction of images are correctly labeled as authentic or tampered.
\end{itemize}

An important methodological note: early experiments computed metrics across all images (both authentic and tampered), which \textit{inflated} results because authentic images with all-zero ground truth masks always score perfect Dice/IoU/F1. From experiment vR.P.3 onward, all segmentation metrics are computed on tampered images only.


% ==================== RESEARCH JOURNEY ====================
\section{Research Journey}

This project did not arrive at its final approach on the first attempt. The path included multiple failed approaches, each teaching lessons that directly shaped the next one. We document all four tracks here because the failures were as informative as the successes.

\subsection{Track 1: Documentation-First (v0x) --- Failed}

The project began with an extensive literature review. Documentation was written before any code: architecture designs, dataset analyses, and training plans. Too many ideas from research papers were added simultaneously, leading to a complex system on paper that was never tested.

\textbf{Lesson:} Documentation without experimentation leads to untested assumptions. Start coding and validating early.

\subsection{Track 2: Kaggle Notebook Reproduction (vK) --- Failed}

A promising Kaggle notebook for image tampering detection was found and adapted. However, an audit revealed \textbf{data leakage} --- test images were leaking into training, inflating reported accuracy to $\sim$89.75\%. After fixing the leakage, the model (training from scratch on $\sim$10K images with 31.6M parameters) achieved only Tampered~F1~=~0.4101.

\textbf{Lesson:} Always audit data pipelines for leakage. Training from scratch on small datasets is insufficient.

\subsection{Track 3: Research Paper Reproduction (vR) --- Archived}

The project pivoted to reproducing a published paper~\cite{nagm2024etasr}, achieving a best classification accuracy of 90.23\%. However, this architecture was classification-only --- it could not produce a localization mask.

\textbf{Lesson:} Verify that the base architecture supports all required tasks before investing in ablation studies.

\subsection{Track 4: Pretrained Ablation Study (vR.P) --- Final Approach}

Armed with lessons from all prior failures, the final approach used:
\begin{itemize}
    \item A \textbf{pretrained encoder} (ResNet-34 on ImageNet) to avoid the small-dataset problem.
    \item A \textbf{UNet segmentation model} for pixel-level localization.
    \item \textbf{ELA preprocessing} (from the ETASR track insight) to give the model forensic input.
    \item \textbf{Single-variable ablation:} exactly one change per experiment.
    \item \textbf{Weights \& Biases} for experiment tracking and reproducibility.
\end{itemize}

This is the track that produced all final results reported below.


