% ==================== ABLATION STUDY ====================
\section{Ablation Study}

The ablation study is the core contribution of this work. Each experiment changed \textit{exactly one variable} from a baseline, enabling clear cause-and-effect analysis. This section organizes findings by category.

\subsection{Impact Hierarchy}

Table~\ref{tab:impact} ranks all modifications by their impact on Pixel~F1 relative to the ELA baseline (P.3, F1=0.6920).

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Ablation Impact Hierarchy (Delta from ELA Baseline P.3)}
\label{tab:impact}
\begin{tabular}{c l l c}
\toprule
\textbf{Rank} & \textbf{Category} & \textbf{Change} & \textbf{$\Delta$ F1 (pp)} \\
\midrule
1 & Input & Multi-Q RGB ELA 9ch (P.19) & +10.45 \\
2 & Input & Multi-Q ELA gray (P.15) & +4.09 \\
3 & Input & ELA+DCT fusion (P.17) & +3.82 \\
4 & Architecture & CBAM attention (P.10) & +3.57 \\
5 & Training & Extended training (P.7) & +2.34 \\
6 & Input & RGB+ELA fusion (P.4) & +1.33 \\
7 & Training & Progressive unfreeze (P.8) & +0.65 \\
8 & Training & Augmentation (P.12) & +0.48 \\
9 & Loss & Focal+Dice (P.9) & +0.03 \\
10 & Evaluation & TTA (P.14b) & \textbf{$-$5.32} \\
11 & Input & DCT-only (P.16) & \textbf{$-$37.11} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The hierarchy is clear and consistent:

\begin{center}
\textbf{Input representation $>$ Attention mechanisms $>$ Training configuration $>$ Loss function}
\end{center}


\subsection{Input Representation (Dominant Factor)}

This was the most impactful category across the entire study.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{RGB to ELA (P.3):} +23.74pp Pixel~F1. The single largest improvement in the study. False positive rate dropped from 22.6\% to 2.7\%.
    \item \textbf{Multi-Q ELA grayscale (P.15):} +4.09pp from P.3. Three grayscale ELA maps at Q=75/85/95 capture complementary forensic signals.
    \item \textbf{Multi-Q RGB ELA 9-channel (P.19):} +10.45pp from P.3. Keeping full RGB color information in each ELA map (rather than converting to grayscale) was worth an additional +6.36pp over the grayscale variant.
    \item \textbf{DCT-only (P.16):} $-$37.11pp. Catastrophic failure. Block-level frequency features alone are completely insufficient.
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Encoder Architecture}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{CBAM attention (P.10):} +3.57pp from P.3. Best architectural modification. Achieved the lowest false positive rate (2.0\%).
    \item \textbf{ResNet-50 (P.5):} F1=0.5137 on RGB (2.86$\times$ more parameters, still below ELA on ResNet-34).
    \item \textbf{EfficientNet-B0 (P.6):} F1=0.5217 on RGB (smallest model, but still far below ELA results).
\end{itemize}

This demonstrates that \textbf{ELA input on ResNet-34} outperforms larger encoders on raw RGB --- input preprocessing matters more than encoder capacity.


\subsection{Training Strategies}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Extended training (P.7):} +2.34pp. The 25-epoch default was premature; the best epoch was at epoch~36.
    \item \textbf{Data augmentation (P.12):} +0.48pp Pixel F1 but achieved the best image-level accuracy (88.48\%).
    \item \textbf{Focal+Dice loss (P.9):} +0.03pp (essentially neutral). Focal Loss~\cite{lin2017focal} concentrates on hard examples, but the Dice component already handles class imbalance.
    \item \textbf{TTA (P.14b):} $-$5.32pp. Averaging across flipped views smooths sharp mask boundaries, destroying localization precision.
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Diminishing Returns}

After Pixel~F1 $\sim$0.78, combining improvements shows diminishing returns. For example, vR.P.30.1 (Multi-Q ELA + CBAM + 50 epochs) = 0.7762, which did \textit{not} surpass P.19's 0.7965. This suggests the model approaches the ceiling of what the dataset and architecture can support.


