% ==================== ERROR ANALYSIS ====================
\section{Error Analysis}

\subsection{False Positive and False Negative Rates}

Table~\ref{tab:error_rates} shows how false positive (FP) and false negative (FN) rates evolved across key configurations.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{False Positive and False Negative Rates}
\label{tab:error_rates}
\begin{tabular}{l c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Configuration} & \textbf{FP Rate} & \textbf{FN Rate} \\
\midrule
RGB baseline (P.1) & 22.6\% & 40.4\% \\
ELA baseline (P.3) & 2.7\% & 28.6\% \\
CBAM attention (P.10) & 2.0\% & 28.3\% \\
Data augmentation (P.12) & 2.6\% & 24.6\% \\
TTA (P.14b) & 1.2\% & 29.3\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

ELA reduces the false positive rate dramatically (22.6\% $\rightarrow$ 2.7\%). CBAM further reduces it to 2.0\%. The remaining errors are primarily false negatives --- the model misses some tampered regions, particularly:

\begin{itemize}
    \item Subtle copy-move forgeries where source and target textures are very similar.
    \item Very small tampered regions ($<$2\% of image area).
    \item Images that have been re-saved multiple times, destroying the ELA signal.
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Best Model Detailed Metrics}

Table~\ref{tab:detailed_metrics} presents the full metric breakdown for the best model (P.15 / P.19), showing the precision-recall trade-off.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Detailed Metrics for the Best Grayscale-ELA Model (P.15)}
\label{tab:detailed_metrics}
\begin{tabular}{l c}
\toprule
\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Value} \\
\midrule
Pixel F1 & 0.7329 \\
Pixel IoU & 0.5785 \\
Pixel AUC & 0.9608 \\
Pixel Precision & 0.8409 \\
Pixel Recall & 0.6496 \\
Image Accuracy & 87.53\% \\
Image Macro F1 & 0.8660 \\
Image ROC-AUC & 0.9423 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The model achieves high precision (0.8409) but moderate recall (0.6496) --- it is confident when it flags a region as tampered, but it misses some tampered areas.


% ==================== REPRODUCIBILITY ====================
\section{Reproducibility and Experiment Tracking}

Reproducibility was a core design principle throughout this project.

\subsection{Fixed Experimental Constants}

Every experiment in the vR.P track shares the same dataset, random seed (42), data split (70/15/15 stratified), input resolution (384$\times$384), decoder architecture (UNet with skip connections), batch size (16), and framework (PyTorch + SMP). Only one variable is changed per experiment.

\subsection{Weights \& Biases Integration}

All experiments are logged to a centralized W\&B project, tracking:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Per-epoch:} training loss, validation loss, validation Pixel F1, validation IoU, learning rate.
    \item \textbf{Final test:} all segmentation and classification metrics.
    \item \textbf{Media:} prediction visualization examples.
\end{itemize}

A centralized leaderboard notebook automatically queries the W\&B API to generate up-to-date comparison tables and ablation charts.

\subsection{Reproducibility Verification}

Two experiments (vR.P.3 and vR.P.10) were run twice independently on Kaggle T4 GPUs. Both runs produced identical metrics, confirming the reproducibility of results with seed~42.


% ==================== KEY LEARNINGS ====================
\section{Key Learnings}

The following lessons emerged from the full experimental journey:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Data leakage destroys credibility.} The Kaggle baseline appeared to work well but had inflated results due to test data leaking into training. Always audit data pipelines.

    \item \textbf{Pretrained models are essential for small datasets.} Training from scratch on $\sim$10K images learns only low-level features. Pretrained encoders provide rich, generalizable representations.

    \item \textbf{Input representation matters more than architecture.} ELA preprocessing (+23.74pp) and multi-quality ELA (+10.45pp more) produced far larger gains than any architectural change.

    \item \textbf{Change one thing at a time.} Early attempts that added multiple improvements simultaneously led to confusion and failure. Single-variable ablation is the only way to understand what actually works.

    \item \textbf{Negative results are valuable.} Knowing that DCT alone fails ($-$37.11pp) or that TTA hurts localization ($-$5.32pp) prevents wasted effort in future work.

    \item \textbf{Verify the base approach supports all tasks.} An entire research track (vR.x.x) was discontinued because the architecture could only classify, not localize.

    \item \textbf{Track experiments formally.} Weights \& Biases~\cite{wandb2020} made it possible to compare 60+ experiments systematically with reproducible metrics.
\end{enumerate}


% ==================== LIMITATIONS ====================
\section{Limitations}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Single dataset:} All results are on CASIA v2.0 only. Cross-dataset generalization (Columbia, Coverage, NIST) is untested.
    \item \textbf{Fixed resolution:} 384$\times$384 input may lose fine details. Higher resolution (512$\times$512+) may improve boundary precision.
    \item \textbf{Binary segmentation only:} The model treats all tampering as one class. It does not distinguish between splicing and copy-move.
    \item \textbf{No robustness testing:} Behavior against post-processing attacks (JPEG recompression, blur, noise addition) is not evaluated.
    \item \textbf{No SRM noise features:} Spatial Rich Model noise extraction --- used by state-of-the-art systems --- is not yet implemented.
    \item \textbf{Diminishing returns:} After Pixel F1 $\sim$0.80, the current architecture likely needs different techniques (transformers, larger datasets) to push further.
\end{enumerate}


% ==================== FUTURE WORK ====================
\section{Future Work}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Cross-dataset evaluation:} Test on Columbia, Coverage, CoMoFoD, and NIST datasets to verify generalization.
    \item \textbf{Transformer-based encoders:} Swin Transformer or ConvNeXt may capture long-range manipulation patterns better than ResNet.
    \item \textbf{SRM noise filters:} Spatial Rich Model high-pass filters for manipulation trace extraction in the noise domain.
    \item \textbf{Higher resolution:} Test at 512$\times$512 or 640$\times$640 to capture finer boundary details.
    \item \textbf{Ensemble methods:} Combine predictions from multiple ELA variants, CBAM, and augmentation configurations.
    \item \textbf{Multi-class segmentation:} Distinguish splicing from copy-move at the pixel level.
\end{itemize}


% ==================== CONCLUSION ====================
\section{Conclusion}

This report presented a systematic ablation study for image tamper detection and localization on the CASIA~v2.0 dataset. Through 60+ controlled experiments across four research tracks, we demonstrated that:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Input representation is the dominant factor.} Switching from raw RGB to Multi-Quality RGB ELA (9-channel) produced a +34.19 percentage point improvement in Pixel~F1 --- far exceeding any architectural or training change.
    \item \textbf{The best model achieves Pixel F1 = 0.7965, IoU = 0.6615, and Pixel AUC = 0.9665}, using a UNet with a frozen pretrained ResNet-34 encoder and 9-channel multi-quality ELA input.
    \item \textbf{Single-variable ablation discipline} transforms ad-hoc experimentation into systematic scientific investigation, enabling clear cause-and-effect understanding.
    \item \textbf{Failures are as informative as successes.} Each failed research track contributed lessons that directly improved the next approach.
\end{enumerate}

The impact hierarchy established by this study --- \textbf{Input representation $>$ Attention mechanisms $>$ Training configuration $>$ Loss function} --- provides a clear roadmap for future work: invest in better input representations before trying more complex architectures.


